<h3>Aging Potential by Wine Style</h3>
<p><strong>Premium Burgundian Pinot Noir</strong> from producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti can age 15-25 years, while village-level wines peak at 8-12 years. <strong>Bordeaux blends</strong> from classified growths develop for 20-30 years, though Merlot-dominant Right Bank wines mature faster than Cabernet Sauvignon-heavy Left Bank selections.</p>

<p><strong>White wines</strong> vary dramatically: Burgundian Chardonnay from premier cru vineyards ages beautifully for 10-15 years, developing honeyed complexity, while Champagne from houses like Krug can evolve for decades, gaining brioche and hazelnut nuances.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>
<p>During aging, <strong>tannins polymerize and soften</strong>, creating silky textures. Primary fruit flavors (blackberry, cherry) evolve into secondary characteristics—leather, tobacco, forest floor. Tertiary aromatics like truffle and cedar emerge after 10+ years in premium bottles.</p>

<p>Most Christmas dinner wines hit their stride between years 5-12, when fruit concentration balances with developed complexity without losing vibrancy.</p>

<h3>Storage Essentials</h3>
<p>Maintain <strong>55°F (13°C) constant temperature</strong> with 70% humidity. Store bottles horizontally to keep corks moist, preventing oxidation. Avoid vibration and light exposure, which can degrade delicate compounds like anthocyanins responsible for color stability.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p><strong>Proper aging</strong> shows clear, brilliant color with natural sediment formation. Aromatics become more complex rather than muted. <strong>Spoilage signs</strong> include brown edges in reds, musty cork taint, or sharp acetaldehyde notes indicating oxidation. Well-aged wines maintain fruit integration with developed secondary characters, never showing aggressive alcohol heat or flat, tired flavors.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
