  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve red or white wine with Christmas turkey?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For traditional roasted turkey, both work beautifully depending on your preparation. A medium-bodied Pinot Noir from Burgundy or Oregon complements herb-crusted turkey without overwhelming the delicate meat, while a rich Chardonnay from Chablis or California pairs excellently with creamy gravy and butter-basted birds. Consider serving both to accommodate different palates and side dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best wine pairing for Christmas ham with glaze?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sweet glazed ham requires wines with enough acidity to cut through the richness and complement the caramelized sugars. German Riesling Kabinett offers the perfect balance of sweetness and acidity, while a fruit-forward Beaujolais-Villages provides bright cherry notes that enhance honey or maple glazes. For white wine lovers, an Alsatian Gewürztraminer's spice notes beautifully echo traditional ham seasonings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How many bottles of wine should I buy for Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for approximately one bottle per two guests for a 3-4 hour dinner, adjusting for your group's drinking preferences. For a Christmas feast with multiple courses, consider having 2-3 different wine styles available: a sparkling wine for toasts, a lighter wine for appetizers, and a more substantial wine for the main course. Always buy one extra bottle as a backup, especially if you're serving a special vintage.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes with Christmas desserts like pudding and mince pies?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich Christmas desserts pair beautifully with fortified wines that can match their intensity. Port, particularly Tawny Port with its nutty, caramel notes, complements Christmas pudding perfectly, while Moscato d'Asti's light effervescence and sweetness enhance mince pies without being cloying. For chocolate-based desserts, consider a late-harvest Zinfandel or even a quality cream sherry.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant wine for Christmas dinner, and when?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, tannic red wines like Cabernet Sauvignon, Barolo, or Rhône blends benefit from 1-2 hours of decanting before your Christmas meal to soften tannins and open up flavors. Older wines (15+ years) should be decanted just before serving to separate sediment but preserve delicate aromas. White wines and lighter reds like Pinot Noir typically don't require decanting unless they're particularly age-worthy bottles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget-friendly wine that still impresses for Christmas?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Côtes du Rhône offers exceptional value with rich, food-friendly flavors that complement most Christmas dishes for under $20. Spanish Garnacha from regions like Campo de Borja provides impressive complexity and fruit concentration at budget prices, while Portuguese Douro reds offer bold flavors typically found in much pricier wines. For whites, look for Albariño from Rías Baixas or Grüner Veltliner from Austria.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I serve the same wine throughout the entire Christmas meal?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While possible, serving one wine throughout multiple courses limits your pairing potential and guest experience. A versatile medium-bodied wine like Côtes du Rhône or Chianti Classico can work from appetizers through the main course, but consider at least switching to a dessert wine or sparkling wine for toasts. The varied flavors of Christmas dinner—from rich meats to sweet sides—truly benefit from thoughtful wine progression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine mistakes should I avoid when hosting Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Avoid serving wines that are too young and tannic (like big Cabernets) without proper decanting, or wines that are too delicate (like light Pinot Grigio) with rich, heavily seasoned dishes. Don't chill red wines too much or serve whites too warm—proper serving temperature dramatically affects taste. Most importantly, avoid buying wine the day of your dinner; purchase at least a week ahead to allow wines to settle from transport vibration.</p>
